AppCore.name: AppCore
AppCore.description: The AppCore module describes fundamental files without which the app wouldn't work at all.

Alerts.name: Alerts
Alerts.description: The Alerts module handles browsing, viewing and responding to received alerts.

AvailabilityRequests.name: AvailabilityRequests
AvailabilityRequests.description:
This module handles teaching requests.

Functions:
* A user can post a teaching request
* Other users can up-vote that request
* Teachers can respond to a request by creating a teaching session

AvailabilitiesSignUp.name: AvailabilitiesSignUp
AvailabilitiesSignUp.description:
AvailabilitySignUp module

This model handles linking of users to teaching sessions. It includes:
* Signing up
* Inviting users
* Accepting or declining invites
* Administrator priviledges for a given teaching session
* Who is a teacher and who is a student

Availabilities.name: Availabilities
Availabilities.description:
The Availabilities module is the core module for creating and editing availabilities.
It includes setting times and descriptions.

It does not include signing up/inviting people, resources, feedback etc. which are covered in other modules.

Messages.name: Messages
Messages.description:
Messages module

Handles user to user messaging. Essentially a WhatsApp clone.

The same components are used to send messages within the show availability page - Conversations can be tagged with an availability.

Users.name: Users
Users.description: List an email account on the account page with appropriate actions for editing

Help.name: Help
Help.description: Help page. Displays option for about, FAQ, walkthrough

Feedbacks.name: Feedbacks
Feedbacks.description:
Complete a feedback request

This route is NOT a sub-route of app.main because an unauthenticated user could access this to complete a request. Layout is different if someone is logged in.

If the request is completed it will still render the submitted feedback.

Home.name: Home
Home.description: Landing page for the app. Redirect to the teach page.

Directory.name: Directory
Directory.description:
Users Index controller
Allows searching and browsing of users
Should be able to search and filter users

adapter-application.name: adapter-application
adapter-application.description:
Application adapter. Uses devise authorizer, and data adapter mixin from ember-simple-auth for route authentication.

Custom headers pass the application version and environment with each response.

Includes some hack methods to allow side loading from JSONAPI-resources.

authenticator-oslr.name: authenticator-oslr
authenticator-oslr.description: Application autheticator. Basic DeviseAuthenticator with minimal adjust

authorizers-devise.name: authorizers-devise
authorizers-devise.description: Application authorizer. Minor configuration to send correct user_email field name.

initializers-globals.name: initializers-globals
initializers-globals.description:
Injects variables that should be accessible throughout the app into routes, controllers, components and models

Variables injected (from the environment.js file):
apiUrl
cableUrl
appEnvironment
appVersion
enabledModules

Also Injects jobtitles, locations, specialties variables. These should be loaded once on hitting the app.main route (i.e. when logged in).

Injects unread-alerts, to hold alert counts across the app.

initializers-simple-auth-setup.name: initializers-simple-auth-setup
initializers-simple-auth-setup.description:
Injects the current user into the session object

Based on this: http://miguelcamba.com/blog/2015/06/18/how-to-inject-the-current-user-using-ember-simple-auth/

model-alert.name: model-alert
model-alert.description:
Email Account model. A user can have any number of email accounts, which may be confirmed and/or verified.

Confirmed accounts have had their authentication code entered proving that the person owns the email address.

Verified accounts match certain patterns e.g. nhs.net or .ac.uk

model-alertable.description: Models inherited from the alertable class can be polymorphically linked to by alert models

model-user.name: model-user
model-user.description:
Defines a User object.

Properties synchronised with the server-side model:
name, email, bio, password, terms, gmc

Read-only properties (i.e. can't be updated from the Ember app, leading to potential insecurities):
confirmed, avatar_url

PopulateCurrentUser
This method looks up the current user from the session ID

The currentUser service is then populated and injected in all routes, controllers and components
For backwards compatibility it defines some extra variables on the session object
